                  </persName>
             (Police-constable H 133.) On the 18th of August, between eight and nine o'clock in the evening, I was on Tower-hill - I saw the prisoner with a parcel on his shoulder; he was going on between a walk and a run - I suspected all was not right, and followed him; he dropped the parcel - I called to two men to take care of it; I followed and took him in the Minories.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-414-person3367">
                  SAMUEL 
                  EMMERSON
               <interp inst="t18320906-414-person3367" type="surname" value="EMMERSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-414-person3367" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-414-person3367" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am clerk to Mr. Thomas Dowbiggin and another, of Mount-street, Grosvenor-square - this parcel contained the articles stated, and is their goods; I gave it to one of our porters to pack, and he gave it to two carmen - it is addressed to Lord Kinnoul, Duplen-castle, Perth.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183209060166"></xptr>THOMAS COLLINS. I was driving the caravan on that Saturday afternoon - I cannot say where I lost this parcel; I missed it when I got to the wharf - it had been tied to the van with some more.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-414-person3368">
                  JAMES 
                  BRUCE
               <interp inst="t18320906-414-person3368" type="surname" value="BRUCE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-414-person3368" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-414-person3368" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a porter. The officer was talking to me, and he ran off and left me, calling to me to mind the parcel, which I saw on the prisoner's shoulder.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was crossing Tower-hill; I saw the van going on rapidly - the tail-board was down, and this bale fell out; I called to the carman, who did not hear me - I was dragging it towards the light, to see the direction, and the officer took me.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320906-414-verdict2336" type="verdictDescription">
